      "question": "Consider the quadratic equation $x^2 - (p+q)x + pq = 0$. If the roots of this equation are $x_1 = 3$ and $x_2 = 4$, and $p < q$, what is the value of the expression $q^2 - p^2$?",
      "answer": "(C)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "The quadratic equation is $x^2 - (p+q)x + pq = 0$.",
          "By comparing with the standard form $x^2 - (sum of roots)x + (product of roots) = 0$, we identify the sum of roots as $p+q$ and the product of roots as $pq$.",
          "We are given the roots $x_1 = 3$ and $x_2 = 4$.",
          "Thus, $p+q = 3+4 = 7$ and $pq = 3 \\times 4 = 12$.",
          "Since $p < q$, we have $p=3$ and $q=4$.",
          "Calculate $q^2 - p^2 = 4^2 - 3^2 = 16 - 9 = 7$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$x^2 - (p+q)x + pq = 0 \\\\ (x-p)(x-q) = 0 \\\\ \\text{Roots are } p \\text{ and } q. \\\\ \\text{Given } x_1=3, x_2=4 \\text{ and } p < q \\Rightarrow p=3, q=4. \\\\ q^2 - p^2 = 4^2 - 3^2 \\\\ = 16 - 9 \\\\ = 7$"
      },
